        <div type="edition"><!-- transcription goes here -->
            <ab>
                <lb n="1"/><expan><abbr>D</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan> <g type="hedera"/> <expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>anibus</ex></expan>.
                <lb n="2"/><persName><name type="praenomen" key="Gellius">Cellio</name> <name type="gentilicium" key="Balentinus">Balentino</name></persName>,
                <lb n="3"/>marito bene mere<hi rend="ligature">nt</hi>i
                <lb n="4"/><persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Sertoria">Sertoria</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Calliste">Calliste</name></persName> <g type="hedera"/>,
                <lb n="5"/>cum quo vixit <expan><abbr>ann</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan>
                <lb n="6"/><num value="10" type="cardinal">X</num>. Bita sine lite.
            </ab></div>
        
        
                <div type="translation">
                    <p/>
                </div>
            
        
        
                <div type="commentary"><!-- notes go here -->
            <p> Although the use of "b" for "v" is documented early in the empire, the merger becomes more stable in Rome after the 4th century CE. J.L. Barbarino offers an in depth study on the phenomenon (Barbarino, J.L. 1978. "The Evolution of the Latin /b/-/u#/ Merger." Chapel Hill. "Balentinus" and "bita," which are easily understood as the result of this merger, represent actual pronunciation and not a mistake or misunderstanding on the part of the scribe. The use of "c" for "g" as seen in "Cellio" (line 2), is very common. The expression of a life without quarrel is not unfrequently articulated on funerary monuments from one spouse to another, but this exact combination of words ("vita sine lite") occurs only in this inscription. "Sine crimine" and "sine dolore" (often in combination with one another) are the more common examples. "Sine lite" and its alternatives do occur more frequently with a form of the verb "vivo" rather than set off in a phrase with the noun "vita."  </p></div>
            
        
        
